      <hedline>
        <hl1>America's Endless War on Fat</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from David English, commenting on series of articles on overweight Americans, says genetics may play role, but less obvious culprit is television, which features nonstop food</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''No Days Off Are Allowed, Experts Argue'' (''The Fat Epidemic,'' front page, Oct. 18):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''No Days Off Are Allowed, Experts Argue'' (''The Fat Epidemic,'' front page, Oct. 18):</p>
        <p>Yes, genetics plays a big role in how much each of us weighs. But while our genes have not evolved in the last several decades, the obesity rate in America has ballooned. Television has been blamed for much of this, exemplifying as it does our increasingly sedentary lifestyle. But a less obvious culprit is what we see on commercial television: nonstop food.</p>
        <p>Our great-great-grandparents were not only of necessity more physically active than we are, they also did not subject themselves to a nightly electronic gantlet of heavily caloric temptation. Nor had convenience stores, 24-hour supermarkets and candy vending machines been invented.</p>
        <p>Certainly, there was junk food a century ago, but it didn't dominate numerous aisles of the general store.</p>
        <p>DAVID ENGLISH  Somerville, Mass., Oct. 18, 2000</p>
      </block>
